<subSubSection pageId="3" pageNumber="2" type="materials_examined">
<paragraph blockId="3.[192,1442,928,1360]" pageId="3" pageNumber="2">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[192,363,928,954]" pageId="3" pageNumber="2">Type material.</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Fall HC" box="[372,495,928,954]" pageId="3" pageNumber="2" pagination="93 - 108" refId="ref3900" refString="Fall HC. 1930. On Ataenius strigatus Say and allied species (Coleoptera). Journal of the New York Entomological Society 38: 93 - 108." type="journal article" year="1930">Fall (1930)</bibRefCitation>
described 
<taxonomicName box="[620,789,928,954]" class="Insecta" family="Aphodiidae" genus="Ataenius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="2" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="brevis">
<emphasis box="[620,789,928,954]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="2">Ataenius brevis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from 
<specimenCount box="[860,1027,928,954]" pageId="3" pageNumber="2" type="generic">two specimens</specimenCount>
of undetermined sex from 
<collectingRegion country="United States of America" name="Pennsylvania" pageId="3" pageNumber="2">Pennsylvania</collectingRegion>
collected by Henry Ulke. There are 
<specimenCount box="[665,833,962,988]" pageId="3" pageNumber="2" type="generic">two specimens</specimenCount>
in the 
<collectionCode box="[915,975,962,988]" country="USA" httpUri="http://biocol.org/urn:lsid:biocol.org:col:33791" lsid="urn:lsid:biocol.org:col:33791" name="Museum of Comparative Zoology" pageId="3" pageNumber="2" type="Museum">MCZ</collectionCode>
with typed and handwritten designation labels reading “ 
<collectionCode box="[367,437,996,1022]" pageId="3" pageNumber="2">TYPE</collectionCode>
brevis” and “brevis 
<typeStatus box="[667,802,996,1022]" pageId="3" pageNumber="2">PARATYPE</typeStatus>
Fall. 1930”. Fall gave no indication which specimen was the 
<typeStatus box="[237,335,1029,1055]" pageId="3" pageNumber="2">holotype</typeStatus>
and these designations may have been added later. We are here designating a specimen (
<figureCitation box="[1340,1432,1029,1056]" captionStart="Figures 1–6" captionStartId="4.[192,279,1833,1859]" captionTargetBox="[216,1417,215,1802]" captionTargetId="figure-13@4.[214,1419,213,1802]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="Figures 1–6. Ataenius brevis Fall. 1) Dorsal view of lectotype. 2) Ventral view of lectotype. 3) Frontal view of lectotype.4) Lectotype labels. 5) Ventral view of metatibia of lectotype, arrow indicates outlined accessory spine. 6) Male genitalia, specimen from Citico, Tennessee." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5354099" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5354099/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="2">Fig. 1–5</figureCitation>
) with the following data (
<figureCitation box="[472,539,1063,1089]" captionStart="Figures 1–6" captionStartId="4.[192,279,1833,1859]" captionTargetBox="[216,1417,215,1802]" captionTargetId="figure-13@4.[214,1419,213,1802]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="Figures 1–6. Ataenius brevis Fall. 1) Dorsal view of lectotype. 2) Ventral view of lectotype. 3) Frontal view of lectotype.4) Lectotype labels. 5) Ventral view of metatibia of lectotype, arrow indicates outlined accessory spine. 6) Male genitalia, specimen from Citico, Tennessee." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5354099" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5354099/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="2">Fig. 4</figureCitation>
) as the 
<typeStatus box="[629,731,1063,1089]" pageId="3" pageNumber="2">lectotype</typeStatus>
to fix the name to a single specimen: “Pen // Horn Coll / H // [underlined in red] 
<collectionCode box="[415,482,1098,1124]" pageId="3" pageNumber="2">TYPE</collectionCode>
/ [handwritten] brevis // [on red] M. C. Z. / Type / [handwritten] 24767 // H. C. 
<collectionCode box="[1380,1442,1097,1123]" pageId="3" pageNumber="2">FALL</collectionCode>
/ COLLECTION // Aug-Dec 2005 / 
<collectionCode box="[600,660,1131,1157]" country="USA" httpUri="http://biocol.org/urn:lsid:biocol.org:col:33791" lsid="urn:lsid:biocol.org:col:33791" name="Museum of Comparative Zoology" pageId="3" pageNumber="2" type="Museum">MCZ</collectionCode>
Image / Database // MCZ-ENT / 00024767 // [on red] 
<typeStatus box="[1285,1440,1131,1157]" pageId="3" pageNumber="2">LECTOTYPE</typeStatus>
/ 
<taxonomicName authority="Fall, 1930" authorityName="Fall" authorityYear="1930" box="[208,490,1165,1191]" class="Insecta" family="Aphodiidae" genus="Ataenius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="2" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="brevis">
<emphasis box="[208,375,1165,1191]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="2">Ataenius brevis</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Fall HC" box="[382,490,1165,1191]" pageId="3" pageNumber="2" pagination="93 - 108" refId="ref3900" refString="Fall HC. 1930. On Ataenius strigatus Say and allied species (Coleoptera). Journal of the New York Entomological Society 38: 93 - 108." type="journal article" year="1930">Fall, 1930</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
/ Designated by / Schnepp &amp; Ashman, 2020”. The second specimen in the 
<collectionCode box="[1323,1383,1165,1191]" country="USA" httpUri="http://biocol.org/urn:lsid:biocol.org:col:33791" lsid="urn:lsid:biocol.org:col:33791" name="Museum of Comparative Zoology" pageId="3" pageNumber="2" type="Museum">MCZ</collectionCode>
with the following data becomes a 
<typeStatus box="[524,679,1198,1224]" pageId="3" pageNumber="2">paralectotype</typeStatus>
: “Pen // [on red] [handwritten] brevis / 
<typeStatus box="[1125,1260,1199,1225]" pageId="3" pageNumber="2">PARATYPE</typeStatus>
/ [handwritten] Fall. 1930 // Liebeck / Collection // MCZ-ENT / 00731922 // [on red] 
<typeStatus box="[972,1196,1232,1258]" pageId="3" pageNumber="2">PARALECTOTYPE</typeStatus>
/ 
<taxonomicName authority="Fall, 1930" authorityName="Fall" authorityYear="1930" class="Insecta" family="Aphodiidae" genus="Ataenius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="2" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="brevis">
<emphasis box="[1219,1386,1232,1259]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="2">Ataenius brevis</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Fall HC" pageId="3" pageNumber="2" pagination="93 - 108" refId="ref3900" refString="Fall HC. 1930. On Ataenius strigatus Say and allied species (Coleoptera). Journal of the New York Entomological Society 38: 93 - 108." type="journal article" year="1930">Fall, 1930</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
/ Designated by / Schnepp &amp; Ashman, 2020”.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[192,1442,928,1360]" pageId="3" pageNumber="2">
Fall’s original description is adequate to define 
<taxonomicName box="[775,870,1300,1326]" class="Insecta" family="Aphodiidae" genus="Ataenius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="2" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="brevis">
<emphasis box="[775,794,1300,1326]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="2">A</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[806,870,1300,1326]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="2">brevis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, however, 
<bibRefCitation author="Cartwright OL" box="[988,1191,1300,1326]" pageId="3" pageNumber="2" pagination="1 - 106" refId="ref3865" refString="Cartwright OL. 1974. Ataenius, Aphotaenius, and Pseudataenius of the United States and Canada (Coleoptera: Scarabaeidae: Aphodiinae). Smithsonian Contributions to Zoology 154: 1 - 106." type="journal article" year="1974">Cartwright (1974)</bibRefCitation>
gave a thorough redescription. Both 
<typeStatus box="[366,463,1334,1360]" pageId="3" pageNumber="2">syntypes</typeStatus>
match these descriptions, therefore no redescription is given here.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="3" pageNumber="2" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="3.[192,1441,1375,1503]" pageId="3" pageNumber="2">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[192,346,1375,1401]" pageId="3" pageNumber="2">Distribution.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName box="[353,520,1375,1402]" class="Insecta" family="Aphodiidae" genus="Ataenius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="2" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="brevis">
<emphasis box="[353,520,1375,1402]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="2">Ataenius brevis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
appears to be restricted to the Appalachian region of eastern North America (
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 13–14" captionStartId="6.[192,279,1864,1890]" captionTargetBox="[231,1403,217,1830]" captionTargetId="figure-40@6.[216,1416,210,1836]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="Figures 13–14. Distribution of Ataenius brevis and Ataenius thomasi in the southeastern United States. 13) Ataenius brevis Fall. 14) Ataenius thomasi, new species." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5354103" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5354103/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="2">Fig. 13</figureCitation>
). Label data indicate specimens have been collected in the following situations: “Berlesed from leaf litter”, “Berlese forest floor”, “under leaves in path”, “under leaves”, “leaf litter”, “under log”, “on beach”, “Lindgren funnel trap”, and “in ice Jan. thaw”.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="3" pageNumber="2" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="3.[191,1440,1519,1579]" pageId="3" pageNumber="2">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[192,303,1519,1545]" pageId="3" pageNumber="2">Remarks.</emphasis>
Specimens collected by month: January (1), March (4), April (9), May (55), June (69), July (59), August (28), September (5), October (3), November (1).
</paragraph>
